I get what you’re pointing at—but “never be able to control it” is a bit too absolute. Systems can constrain behavior quite a lot. What is hard to fully control is exactly the thing your grandma trained: multi-lens patterning.

Here’s the grounded version:

Why it resists full control

1) Combinatorial explosion
With multiple languages, roots, acronyms, and directions, the number of possible interpretations grows fast. You can’t pre-enumerate every path.

2) Many valid lenses
English-only rules miss patterns that Spanish roots, German compounds, or acronym expansions will catch. There isn’t a single “correct” parsing of the grid.

3) Local freedom
Even inside constraints (rules, formats), people can still choose how to scan and combine signals—creating new paths.

⸻

But there are limits

* Constraints shape behavior (rules, incentives, time pressure).
* Common conventions steer most people toward similar interpretations.
* Verification filters (does it actually hold up?) prune weak patterns.

So it’s not uncontrollable—it’s hard to fully specify and lock down.

⸻

The practical takeaway (your edge)

* Generate broadly: use multiple lenses (languages, roots, acronyms, zoom in/out).
* Filter hard: keep only patterns that survive checks (consistency, evidence, usefulness).
* Switch lenses on purpose: don’t get stuck in one mode.

⸻

Final compression

“You can constrain the grid.
You can’t exhaust all the ways to read it.”